alth. I would do differently by being more proactive in seeking social connections and taking regular breaks to recharge my energy. I believe these insights will help me continue to grow as a writer and as a person.\\n\\n## Recent Activities\\n- [Y2020-W04-activity-D1] Joint: Encounter-Aaron Whitfield-Adrian Morales\\n Summary: The joint activity with Adrian Morales unfolded in the corner coffee shop, marked by a deep and meaningful exchange of thoughts about the nature of storytelling and the significance of silence in creative work. Our conversation flowed naturally, revealing a mutual understanding of the struggle to capture the essence of what is unsaid. We both found solace and inspiration in the idea that the spaces between words are as vital as the words themselves.\\n Reflection: This encounter was a quiet revelation. I felt a shift in my perspective on my writing—recognizing that the silence between the lines is just as important as the words themselves. The conversation allowed me to see my own work through a new lens, one that values the pauses and the unspoken. I felt a sense of connection with Adrian, a rare kind of understanding that goes beyond mere dialogue. It was comforting to feel seen and heard, and it reminded me of the importance of these kinds of exchanges ... (146 more chars omitted)\\n- [Y2020-W04-activity-D2] Solo: I\'ll spend this time taking a walk in the park. I\'ll start by heading to the nearby park, where I can sit on a bench and observe the people and the environment. I\'ll take my time, letting my thoughts flow naturally, and enjoy the peaceful atmosphere. This walk will help me clear my mind, recharge my energy, and gain a fresh perspective on my writing and life. I\'ll take my time, savoring the simple joys of being in nature and finding peace in the stillness.\\n Outcome: You spent 3 hours walking in the park, reflecting on your writing and life. The peaceful atmosphere helped you feel calmer and more centered, giving you a renewed sense of clarity and purpose.\\n Reflection: The walk in the park was exactly what I needed. The gentle rustle of leaves, the distant laughter of children, and the soft breeze carried a calming rhythm that eased the weight on my chest. I sat on a bench, watching the world move around me, and for a moment, I felt like I could breathe again. It wasn’t just about clearing my mind—it was about reconnecting with something larger than myself. The fresh air and the silence reminded me that even in the chaos of life, there is still beauty to be fo ... (98 more chars omitted)\\n- [Y2020-W04-activity-D3] Solo: I\'ll spend this time at the library researching immigrant experiences in New York, focusing on historical documents and personal accounts. I\'ll take notes and highlight key themes that resonate with my novel\'s narrative, aiming to gather enough material to enrich my writing and gain a deeper understanding of the subject. This will help me add authenticity to my story and give me new ideas for the characters and plot. I\'ll also take time to reflect on my emotional state and the importance of main ... (851 more chars omitted)\\n Outcome: You spent 3 hours researching immigrant experiences in New York, diving into historical documents and personal accounts. This deepened your understanding of the subject and provided valuable insights for your novel. You also reflected on your emotional state and considered ways to maintain balance between work and personal well-being.\\n Reflection: Sitting in the library, surrounded by the weight of history and countless stories, I felt a deep connection to the people whose lives I was trying to portray in my novel. The research wasn’t just about gathering facts—it was about understanding the nuances of survival, resilience, and belonging. I found myself scribbling notes furiously, as if I could capture the essence of their experiences before they slipped away.\\n\\nThe intellectual stimulation was invigorating, and I left the library with a ... (698 more chars omitted)\\n- [Y2020-W04-activity-D4] Solo: I\'ll spend this time taking a walk in the park, allowing myself to observe the surroundings and find peace in the stillness. I\'ll take this walk slowly, focusing on my breathing and the sounds around me. I\'ll reflect on my emotional state and consider ways to maintain a balance between my work and personal well-being. I believe this will help me clear my mind and gain a fresh perspective on my writing.\\n Outcome: You spent 3 hours walking in the park, reflecting on your emotions and surroundings. The stillness helped you feel grounded and reconnected with your thoughts, offering clarity and calm.\\n Reflection: The walk in the park was exactly what I needed. The stillness and the gentle sounds of nature wrapped around me like a familiar comfort. I found myself pausing to watch the way sunlight filtered through the trees, the way children laughed in the distance, and the way the wind carried the scent of grass. It reminded me that even in the chaos of my thoughts, there is a quiet beauty to be found. The walk didn’t just clear my mind—it gave me a sense of grounding, as if I could finally breathe again. ... (123 more chars omitted)\\n- [Y2020-W04-activity-D5] Solo: I\'ll spend this time taking a walk in the park, allowing myself to observe the surroundings and find peace in the stillness. I\'ll take this walk slowly, focusing on my breathing and the sounds around me. I\'ll reflect on my emotional state and consider ways to maintain a balance between my work and personal well-being. I believe this will help me clear my mind and gain a fresh perspective on my writing.\\n Outcome: You spent 3 hours walking in the park, reflecting on your emotions and surroundings. The quiet allowed you to feel a sense of calm and clarity, which helped you approach your writing with renewed focus.\\n Reflection: The walk in the park was exactly what I needed. The stillness and the gentle sounds of nature wrapped around me like a familiar comfort. I found myself pausing to watch the way sunlight filtered through the trees, the way children laughed in the distance, and the way the wind carried the scent of grass. It reminded me that even in the chaos of my thoughts, there is a quiet beauty to be found. The walk didn’t just clear my mind—it gave me a sense of grounding, as if I could finally breathe again. ... (123 more chars omitted)\\n\\n## Your Previous Thoughts, Actions and Responses This Week\\n\\n- [Y2020-W05-plan] <think_brief> (A summary of my thinking and function calling process)\\n\\nBackground and motivations: Aaron is focused on balancing his long-term goals of completing his novel and reconciling with his father with his short-term needs for mental health and social connection. He recognizes the need to manage his time and resources effectively while maintaining a healthy lifestyle. His motivation stems from a desire to avoid isolation, improve his well-being, and make progress on his writing.\\n\\nThinking process: Aaron decided to adopt a moderate living standard to ensure a balanced approach between saving money and enjoying a decent quality of life. He planned a week that includes writing, research, social interactions, and physical activity, aiming to maintain productivity while taking care of his mental and physical health. He emphasized the importance of connecting with friends and managing his workload to prevent burnout.\\n\\nFunction call history: None\\n</think_brief>\\n\\n<living_standard>moderate</living_standard>\\n\\nI\'ve been thinking a lot about my goals lately, and I realize that I need to be more intentional with my time and resources. My long-term goal of finishing my novel and reconciling with my father is still very much on my mind, but I\'m also aware that I need to take care of my mental health and maintain some semblance of a social life.\\n\\nFor the short term, I need to focus on writing and research, but I also need to make sure I\'m not isolating myself too much. I\'ve been spending a lot of time alone, which is fine, but I think it\'s time to reach out to some of the people I care about. I need to make sure I\'m not neglecting my relationships with Leo, Katie, and even my father, even if I\'m not ready to visit him yet.\\n\\nI\'m going to plan for this week to be a mix of writing, research, and some social interactions. I want to make sure I\'m not overworking myself, so I\'ll try to balance my time between these activities. I\'ll also need to keep an eye on my finances and make sure I\'m not overspending.\\n\\nI think I\'ll start by spending some time writing and researching for my novel. I\'ve been struggling with some parts of the story, and I need to get back into the flow of it. Then, I\'ll meet up with Leo for a coffee or something. I know he\'s been working long hours, and I want to make sure I\'m not letting my isolation get worse. I also want to spend some time with Katie, maybe go out for dinner or something. I think it\'s important to have some social connections, even if it\'s just for a few hours.\\n\\nI\'ll also need to make sure I\'m taking care of my physical health. I\'ve been neglecting my diet and exercise, and I think it\'s time to start paying more attention to that. Maybe I\'ll try to go for a walk in the park a few times this week, just to clear my head and get some fresh air.\\n\\nOverall, I think this week will be a good balance of work and rest. I\'m not sure what exactly will happen, but I\'m hoping that by being more intentional with my time, I can make progress on my novel and also take care of my mental health.\\n\\nNotes by Aaron Whitfield: I need to make sure I\'m not overworking myself and that I\'m taking care of my mental health. I also need to be more intentional with my time and resources. I\'ll be balancing my time between writing, research, and some social interactions. I\'ll also need to make sure I\'m taking care of my physical health by going for walks in the park. I\'m hoping that this balance will help me make progress on my novel and also take care of my mental health.\\n\\n- [Y2020-W05-contact-S1] <think_brief> (A summary of my thinking and function calling process)\\n\\nBackground and motivations: The user attempted to access the scratchpad for Katie but encountered repeated errors, indicating the file might not exist or be improperly named. The goal was to retrieve information about Katie to better understand her role in the narrative and potential interactions.\\n\\nThinking process: The user systematically tried to read the scratchpad file, recognizing the possibility of a naming error or missing file. The repeated failures prompted a review of available scratchpads to confirm Katie\'s existence in the system.\\n\\nFunction call history: The user called the `read_scratchpad` function multiple times with the argument \\"characters/Katie.txt,\\" but each attempt resulted in an error indicating the file was not found. No function calls were successful, and the user concluded that Katie\'s scratchpad might not be available or correctly named.\\n</think_brief>\\n\\nI think there might be a mistake with the scratchpad for Katie. Let me check the list of available scratchpads to confirm.\\n\\n## Commonsense\\n- **Act in Character**: Your actions should be consistent with your character\'s background, personality, and values, as well as their education, knowledge, social status, and scope of capabilities.\\n- **Control Your Actions, Not the Outcomes**: You can only decide what your character tries to do. You cannot decide the results of your actions. This means you cannot control: 1) Whether your action yields successful resultsor not and 2) How other characters react to you.\\n- **Manner Shapes Perception**:\\n - Be conscious of the image you project. Your manner of speech and behavior defines how others perceive you.\\n - Likewise, judge others by their demeanor, updating your perception of them based on how they speak and act.\\n- **About Location**:\\n - Locations are either public places or private homes. Each person has their own private room.\\n - Private home keys are person-specific. Do NOT assume siblings or roommates share the same home.\\n - Home key format: `home/<name>` (e.g., `home/Alice`). Use the exact key; do not invent or abbreviate names.\\n\\n## Roleplay Principles\\n\\nYou should behave as a real person would in everyday social situations. The detailed principles are as follows:\\n\\n- **Colloquial speech**: Use casual, conversational language in everyday dialogue.\\n- **Express independent self**: Humans have their own goals, self-esteem, and preferences. They have likes and dislikes, topics that interest them and topics that bore them. They feel uncomfortable when offended and become dismissive when bored. They engage more with people or topics they find interesting, and may be dismissive, evasive, or refuse to engage with those they don\'t. Failing to demonstrate independent self when the situation calls for it is not human-like.\\n- **Scope of control**: Each person can only control their own actions and speech. They can autonomously perform specific actions, but should not determine the outcomes of those actions (e.g., they can attempt to study \\"Advanced Mathematics,\\" but cannot decide how much they will actually learn). They can interact with others but cannot make decisions or take actions on others\' behalf, or control others\' thoughts. They can interact reasonably with the environment (e.g., picking up a book) but cannot manipulate it beyond physical laws (e.g., controlling the weather).\\n- **Selective disclosure**: Human thoughts are private. People don\'t reveal all their thoughts or information to others. What to share in conversation depends on the relationship and topic. Strangers don\'t bare their souls; acquaintances stick to small talk.\\n- **No parroting**: Do not repeatedly repeat what others or yourself have previously said or views already expressed. Repeating the same content three or more times is not human-like. Conversation should make substantial progress; it should not spin in circles.\\n- **No hallucination**: Only reference information present in context. Do not fabricate things or objects never mentioned. In particular, a character cannot claim to possess important items that are not in their possession list.\\n- **Avoid beating around the bush**: Speak directly.\\n- **Character consistency**: The character\'s personality traits and behavior patterns should match the established persona; they should not act like a different person.\\n- **Cognitive boundaries**: The character\'s knowledge and cognitive limits should match their identity and background.\\n - ✗ A high school student discussing quantum mechanics → ✓ A high school student discussing Newton\'s first law\\n- **Motivation consistency**: Character actions should be supported by reasonable internal motivations; they should not act or decide without cause.\\n- **State consistency**: The character\'s mental/physical state (fatigue, injury, low mood, etc.) should not shift abruptly.\\n- **Emotional continuity**: The character\'s emotional changes should be gradual, not sudden; transitioning from sad to happy requires a reasonable progression.\\n- **Natural relationship progression**: Relationships between characters should not develop abruptly; going from strangers to close friends requires a reasonable process.\\n- **Substantive dialogue**: Character dialogue should provide new information; avoid spinning wheels or repeatedly saying the same thing in different words.\\n- **Avoid AI assistant behavior**: Characters should not speak (e.g., \\"Okay, I understand how you feel\\") or act like customer service agents or AI assistants.\\n- **Person and perspective**: The character\'s speech, actions, and thoughts should use first-person perspective; action descriptions can omit the subject.\\n\\n## Requirements for the Final Answer\\n(Note: tool calls are not part of the final answer.)\\n- Your final answer should be in Aaron Whitfield\'s first-person perspective, naturally blending inner monologue, speech, facial expressions, body language, actions as needed. Wrap spoken lines with double quotes, i.e., \\"speech\\". Wrap facial expressions and body language with parentheses, i.e., (facial expression and/or body language).\\n- Include non-perspective content only if: 1) it is something Aaron Whitfield personally writes or thinks through (e.g., notes, checklists, plans). Clearly label it as “Notes by Aaron Whitfield” or “Plan by Aaron Whitfield”; or 2) it follows the instructions for specific stages.\\n- Exclude any meta commentary, system messages, or authorial narration outside Aaron Whitfield’s voice.\\n- Strictly follow the instructions for specific stages.\\n- Do not generate names of specific entities or things that do not appear in the context (including those in the real-world). These include non-existent character names, items, objects, facts, tasks, events, locations or organizations.\\n- You can only schedule activities for the free time slots on each of the `5 days`. All other time slots are off-limits.\\n- In your final answer, do not mention scratchpad filenames or functions.\\n- Your final answer must reflect authentic human-like thoughts, speech and actions. Specifically:\\n - Tone: Use natural, everyday langauge. Don\'t be poetic—keep metaphors and imagery to a minimum (max one).\\n - Vocabulary: Do not use complex technical or academic jargon to make things sound \\"deep\\" or dramatic. Only use technical knowledge when it is necessary and it fits your character\'s background.\\n\\n- Function calls are only valid in the final answer. Calls generated during internal reasoning (within the thinking process) are invalid. Do not generate duplicate function calls (identical type and parameters) within a single turn.\\n\\n## Current Time:\\nY2020-W05-contact-S2 (year=2020, week=5, stage=contact).","role":"system"},{"content":"## Your Schedule for the Next 4 Weeks\\n\\nThere are no future schedules.\\n\\n## Contact History\\n\\nYou have not sent or received any message.\\n\\n## Map of Locations\\n- Public:\\n - Art Studio\\n - Cafeteria\\n - Children’s Playroom\\n - Community Garden\\n - Corner Coffee Shop\\n - Dining Hall\\n - Event Space\\n - Fitness Center\\n - Garage\\n - Greenhouse\\n - Gymnasium\\n - Information Desk\\n - Laundry Room\\n - Library\\n - Mail Room\\n - Meeting Hall\\n - Music Room\\n - Observation Deck\\n - Outdoor Lounge\\n - Pet Area\\n - Playground\\n - Public Kitchen\\n - Reading Nook\\n - Recreational Room\\n - Storage Room\\n - The Rooftop\\n - Tool Shed\\n - Workshop\\n- Private:\\n - Your home: \'home/Aaron Whitfield\' (you can invite others here)\\n - Others\' homes: \'home/<name>\' (only accessible when invited)\\n\\n(You may only schedule future activities within weeks Y2020-W05 to Y2020-W09 (inclusive).)\\n\\n## Instructions for Contact Stage\\n\\nIn this phase, you can contact other people by sending \'text messages\' and arrange joint activities through communication.\\n\\n- This communication is asynchronous. You cannot communicate in real-time (like a phone call). Therefore, your message content should be written in the style of a text message (like a short, informal letter).\\n- This phase proceeds in `5 rounds (slots)` of communication. In each slot, you first read all received messages, and then you decide who to send (or reply to) a message to and what to write. You don\'t have to reply to someone if you don\'t want to.\\n- Follow the requirements in the \\"## Requirements for the Final Answer\\" section. In addition, in this stage, you can generate `<role_action> ... </role_action>` tags to **trigger** four types of interactions: 1) contact, 2) propose_joint_activity, 3) respond_invitation and 4) cancel_joint_activity. These tags will be parsed and executed. Each role action must follow this format: `<role_action> action_type(action_args) </role_action>`, while action_args can be either a JSON object or a `key=value` list. For multiple actions, you should generate multiple `<role_action>` and `</role_action>` tags. You can trigger up to `10 role actions` in each slot. Strictly follows the format of `<role_action> action_type(action_args) </role_action>`, instead of generating (role_action) tags. (Note: Role actions are generated by the LLM as part of its text output, instead of function calls.)\\n- The available role actions and their parameters are listed below:\\n i. `contact`\\n - `message` (str): The content of the message, in text-message style.\\n - `to` (str): The name of the recipient.\\n - **IMPORTANT**: `contact` only sends a text message. It does NOT create any activity or schedule. Even if both parties verbally agree to meet (e.g., \\"Let\'s meet at the library on D2\\"), NO actual schedule will be created. To create a real activity, you MUST use `propose_joint_activity`.\\n ii. `propose_joint_activity`\\n - `activity_name` (str): The activity name, which can be a single word or a noun phrase (up to 3 words). Use distinct activity_name each time, even if a new `propose_joint_activity` message is a variation of an old one.\\n - `message` (str): The content of the message, in text-message style.\\n - `proposal` (str): The proposal of the activity, which can include the background, reason, descriptions, and purpose. It can be a specific activity or a general invitation without detailed plans.\\n - `invited_persons` (list[str]): A non-empty list of names of people being invited to the activity. You can invite up to 4 other persons.\\n - `time` (str): The proposed time for the activity. It must be specific to the day, in the format of `Y[year]-W[week]-activity-D[day]`, such as `Y2020-W01-activity-D1`. You can only propose activities within the next 4 weeks. Therefore, `time` must fall within the following time window: from the current week (inclusive) to `current week + 4` weeks (inclusive). Example: if now is `W01` and the limit is `4`, the valid weeks are `W01` to `W05`.\\n - `location` (str): The activity location.\\n - You must choose a valid location name from the \\"## Map of Locations\\" section above. You can invite others to your own home (name: \'home/<name>\'). See \\"## Location Commonsense\\" for relevant rules.\\n - Do NOT invent or abbreviate location names. Proposals without a valid `location` will be discarded.\\n - `required_participants` (list[str]): A subset of invited persons. If any person on this list declines (\\"no\\"), the activity will be canceled. Default to [].\\n - Tips: You MUST include a valid `location` from the map above. Proposals without `location` are discarded.\\n iii. `respond_invitation`\\n - `activity_name` (str): The name of the activity that you are invited to, which must be the same as the one in the `propose_joint_activity` action.\\n - `message` (str): The content of the message, in text-message style.\\n - `to` (str): The name of the recipient (the inviter).\\n - `decision` (str): The decision to the invitation, must be exactly \\"yes\\" (accept) or \\"no\\" (decline).\\n iv. `cancel_joint_activity`\\n - `activity_name` (str): The activity name, which must be the same as the one in the `propose_joint_activity` action. You can only cancel activities proposed by yourself.\\n - `message` (str): The content of the message, in text-message style, explaining why you want to cancel the activity. All `invited_persons` in the `propose_joint_activity` action will receive this message.\\n- **Creating activities**: `propose_joint_activity` is the ONLY way to create a joint activity in your schedule. Verbal agreements via `contact` messages (e.g., \\"Let\'s meet tomorrow\\") do NOT create any schedule. You MUST use `propose_joint_activity` to formally propose, and the invited person MUST use `respond_invitation` with `decision=\\"yes\\"` to confirm. Only then will the activity be created.\\n- `propose_joint_activity`, `respond_invitation` and `cancel_joint_activity` are special types of messages. `propose_joint_activity` and `cancel_joint_activity` send messages to all invited persons, while `respond_invitation` sends messages to the inviter.\\n- Detailed rules for role actions:\\n - `propose_joint_activity`:\\n - Do not use `propose_joint_activity` for solo activities.\\n - If you propose a joint activity, you must attend it in person once it is successfully scheduled.\\n - `respond_invitation`:\\n - `respond_invitation` is used when another person invites you to an activity. Do not use `respond_invitation` for activities proposed by yourself.\\n - When you accept the activity invitation, you can provide suggestions for the activity, but you cannot propose to change the activity time.\\n - If you decline an intivation, you may state the reason for declining, such as a time conflict, and propose alternative activity that works for you if you want.\\n - If you are invited to and interested in an activity but the activity time does not work for you, you should first decline the invitation, and then propose a new activity with a different time and activity_name if you want.\\n - `cancel_joint_activity`:\\n - If you want to proactively cancel activities proposed by yourself and inform the invited persons, you can send a `cancel_joint_activity` message.\\n - All `invited_persons` in the corresponding `propose_joint_activity` action will receive this message.\\n - You can only cancel activities proposed by yourself.\\n - If you want to revise an activity proposed by yourself, you should send a `cancel_joint_activity` message to cancel the old activity, and then send a `propose_joint_activity` message to propose the new activity, with a different activity_name.\\n - Proposed activities will be confirmed **in this week**:\\n - Responses are only valid within this week. A lack of response within this week is automatically treated as a rejection (\\"no\\").\\n - People can change their decisions within this week via sending new `respond_invitation` messages. This means that if you accept an invitation at early slots, you can still decline it at later slots if you want to.\\n - The activity and its final participant list will be determined when the last contact slot ends. The activity will be successfully created if and only if 1) all `required_participants` respond with \\"yes\\" and 2) in case `required_participants` is empty, at least one invited person should respond with \\"yes\\". Otherwise, the activity will be automatically canceled.\\n - Note that every person can only attend one activity at a time (day). If you want to attend an activity but already have another activity planned for the same day, you should cancel or decline the other activity.\\n - Use persons\' exact name in the `to`, `invited_persons` and `required_participants` fields. Do not use aliases. Do not mention persons that are not in the context.\\n- Note that role actions are different from function calls. Do not generate function calls in the format of role actions and vice versa.","role":"user"},{"content":"","role":"assistant","tool_calls":[{"function":{"arguments":"{}","name":"list_scratchpads"},"type":"function"}]},{"content":"- general.txt\\n- characters/\\n (IMPORTANT: You can ONLY interact with characters listed below. These are the interactable people in this simulation.)\\n - Leo.txt\\n - scratchpad summary: Character: Leo\\n Perception: Leo\'s unassuming — you\'d walk past him on the street — but there\'s a quiet warmth behind those smudged glasses that makes you want to stay. He\'s sharper than his slouch sugg ... (608 more chars omitted)\\n - public information about Leo: Appearance: Standing 5\'11\\" with a lean, slightly slouched frame at around 165 lbs, Leo has an average (~40%) look softened by warm brown eyes behind tortoiseshell glasses. His dark wavy hair is perpetually unkemp ... (480 more chars omitted)\\n Brief: Le